devops-exp-6
Manage Kubernetes Resources Using CLI

✅ Step 1 — Start Kubernetes
Copy:
minikube start --driver=dockerkubectl get nodes
✔ Output:
Node status: Ready
👉 Meaning: Kubernetes cluster is running

✅ Step 2 — Create Pod
Copy:
notepad nginx-pod.yaml
Paste:
apiVersion: v1kind: Podmetadata:  name: nginx-podspec:  containers:  - name: nginx    image: nginx    ports:    - containerPort: 80
Save as All Files
Now run:
kubectl apply -f nginx-pod.yamlkubectl get pods
✔ Output:
nginx-pod   Running
👉 Meaning: Pod created successfully

✅ Step 3 — Access Pod
Copy:
kubectl port-forward pod/nginx-pod 8080:80
Open browser:
http://localhost:8080
✔ Output:
NGINX page
👉 Meaning: Pod is working

✅ Step 4 — Create Deployment
Copy:
kubectl create deployment my-nginx --image=nginxkubectl get deployments
✔ Output:
my-nginx   Available
👉 Meaning: Deployment created

✅ Step 5 — Scale Deployment
Copy:
kubectl scale deployment my-nginx --replicas=3kubectl get pods
✔ Output:
3 pods running
👉 Meaning: Scaling worked

✅ Step 6 — Update Deployment
Copy:
kubectl set image deployment/my-nginx nginx=nginx:1.25kubectl rollout status deployment/my-nginx
✔ Output:
successfully rolled out
👉 Meaning: Update successful

✅ Step 7 — Expose Service
Copy:
kubectl expose deployment my-nginx --type=NodePort --port=80kubectl get svcminikube service my-nginx --url
Open URL
✔ Output:
NGINX page
👉 Meaning: Service exposed and accessible

✅ Step 8 — Cleanup
Copy:
kubectl delete deployment my-nginxkubectl delete pod nginx-podminikube stop
👉 Meaning: Resources removed

🧾 What I did in this experiment
In this experiment, I started a Kubernetes cluster using Minikube. I created a Pod using a YAML file and accessed it through the browser. Then I created a Deployment, scaled it to multiple replicas, and updated its image. After that, I exposed the deployment as a service and accessed it using a URL. Finally, I deleted all resources and stopped the cluster.

🎤 Viva line
I used kubectl CLI to create and manage Pods and Deployments, scaled the application, exposed it as a service, and accessed it using Minikube.

✅ Final statement
Kubernetes resources were successfully created, scaled, exposed, and cleaned using kubectl CLI.

